perhaps 20 years to late ... perhaps my pride wouldnâ€™t let me see it. or shame held me down. but me too !
i was 14  and had moved from calgary to castlegar. i didnâ€™t know to many people but i met one girl on my bus and she was so cool , she reminded me of my sister back in calgary. she was dating a older guy .  one weekend i was asked to go camping w them and one of his friends. i probably told my dad and step mom i was staying at her house ... we took one tent and sky vodka ( in our minds it tasted like cotton candy (( before cotton candy flavoured vodka ). we had a fire and my friend and her bf went into the tent so me and this guy ; i actually spoke his name today for the first time in years. (i feel enlightened.... is this realization , what has kept me blind , self sabotaging, abusing drugs and alcohol. this in turn led to mental health issues which iâ€™m now able to remedy. always feeling i was unworthy of friends, healthy relationships all comes back to this ). we walked down towards the lake and sat there talking about who knows what... itâ€™s still very blurry , i remember saying â€œ will you still talk to me tomorrow ?â€ then instantly him rough on top of me , iâ€™m on the rocky ground i blackout. iâ€™m alone iâ€™m the woods, as the sun comes up . i see the blood and i walk down to the lake. itâ€™s cold . i go into the water in my underwear to wash it all away and i swim out off the cliffs. iâ€™m ok , i can swim , i can breathe. if i can get out of this water and climb back up that cliff, then i can do anything â€¢ i did, i went and layed in the tent until my friends came back and took me home. i never talked to him again ..,, but unfortunately i became bitter and mean and angry and as i look back i apologize to those i hurt after that, i became a bully after that and iâ€™m sorry to those i hurt because i didnâ€™t know how to express my feelings. there were so many pent up issues from childhood and this was the catalyst to my angry teenage years, and blind rage filled adolescence... adulthood....iâ€™m going into this new year off of social media so i can work on myself and my goals. it feels so freeing to admit this one incident happened,

what is it exactly? itâ€™s recognizing the ways in which people are discriminated against & oppressed based on their gender, race, class, ability, ethnicity, etc. in society & systems & that these oppressions intersect together. âœ¨audre lorde & kimberle crenshaw were 2 pioneers of these movementsâœ¨ ğŸŒ· for example, a women may face oppression, but a woman who is a person of colour, experiences poverty &/or isnt heterosexual will experience oppression on various levels of intensity. ğŸŒ¸this is why intersectionality is a critical component in feminism - it unpacks the different systems of oppression & how they interact/intersect. it recognizes that feminism is not a â€œone-size-fits-allâ€ movement. itâ€™s more complex & multi-faceted & often does not include the voices & experiences of women of colour, lgbtq+ folk, differently abled bodies, nor does it recognize the different disparities & lack of respect & rights that these individuals receive on a daily basis. ğŸŒ¼ as a white, cis-gendered women, i am working to recognize that while i may face oppression/discrimination for being a women, i do not face the same challenges as others because of my privilege. i am actively trying to incorporate inclusion & intersectionality in my work by educating myself on such issues, creating space for the voices of women from all backgrounds & recognize how i may be participating in systems of oppression against other women.

.
it's not fun and it is exhausting yâ€™all!!
.
i wish i knew the answer to make it stop but i just don't.
.
so tonight i'm going to give myself some grace, take a hot shower (alone ğŸ˜Œ) and go to bed praying that what i did today was enough to make them know they are loved.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
today was my 2nd to last therapy session, not by choice but because our insurance is changing. thereâ€™s some big changes coming that i havenâ€™t quite shared with you yet, but itâ€™s definitely a big transition.
-
a part of me is scared, because iâ€™m not ready to stop therapy. but i am excited for what this new season could mean for our family.
-
as i reflect over the last 20months in processing the hard parts of my story of abandonment and sexual abuse with a therapist who does inner healing, the more iâ€™m seeing iâ€™m not that same girl from when i first started. thereâ€™s been so much growth. my identity as a daughter of god is stronger than ever. i know i havenâ€™t arrived, and iâ€™m still healing but, iâ€™m learning to trust god in deeper ways like never before, iâ€™m learning to trust myself, and iâ€™m open to trusting others again!
-
if youâ€™re local to chicago and know of an affordable therapist, please dm me!! i want to make sure i have something set up in time for feb. i have a few resources in mind, but want to explore all my options.
-
and for my friends who share a similar story, i want you to know you arenâ€™t alone. what happened to you was not your fault. and i believe you!!! i pray that you would find healing, in whatever way that would look like for you!

text: a new report by the urban indian health institute (uihi) on the number of murdered and missing indigenous women and girls found that seattle had the most of any city and washington state had the second highest number of any state. uihi identified 506 unique cases of missing and murdered american indian and alaska native women and girls in 71 cities: 8% of those were domestic violence related; 6% of the victims were sexually assaulted at the time of their disappearance or death; and 4% of the victims were identified as sex workers or victims of trafficking. learn more here: https://wscadv.org/news/uihi-mmiw-report/

the truth is, there will always be other women that are prettier, taller, skinnier, fitter or have things that we donâ€™t possess but at the end of the day we are all women here. so why are we the ones making it harder on ourselves?we arenâ€™t going to grow as women if we are the ones always tearing each other down. we need to help, work together, support, and empower each other because it makes things much easier and better for ourselves....#womanempowerment #woman #love #success #inspiration #positivevibes #fashion #women #womanpower #life #metoo #art #beauty #entrepreneur #beautiful #blogger #womanquotes #melanin #model #feminist #feminism #inspirationalquotes #crown #successfulwomen #lifequotes #motivation #slayqueen #makeuplover

text:
the clothesline by monica mayer (mexico, 1954). @kochibiennale
beside the installation, the artist invited the kochi biennale visitors to share their experiences and responses to violence against women. 
i was very moved to read some of the visitors' notes. to have the courage to write down about their personal traumatic experience mostly during childhood, i applaud them. we as a society should create an environment where everyone feels safe enough to speak about sexual violence.

text:
on the prosecutorsâ€™ intranet, on january 29, 2018, ji-hyun seo wrote about the sexual harassment she suffered throughout her career as a female prosecutor and had an interview with jtbc newsroom, the most trusted and influential news program in south korea. soon after, more women came forward. people became aware of the pervasive and ongoing sexual crimes in many sectors of south korean society and began demanding punishment of the perpetrators and solutions to eradicate and prevent the crimes.

on the new yearâ€™s eve, seo visited two former japanese military sex slaves, bok-dong kim and won-ok gil, at 'í‰í™”ì˜ ìš°ë¦¬ì§‘' (peaceful our house), a home provided by the korean council for justice and remembrance for the issues of military sexual slavery by japan. seo, who ignited the #metoo movement, expressed deep respect to the former japanese military sex slaves who testified, and she stated that they are the real pioneers of the #metoo movement.

mee-hyang yoon, chair of the board of the korean council, said that seo meeting with the two victims is another reminder of how redressing the â€œcomfort womenâ€ history has led to the establishment of an intergenerational alliance.

text:
#barbietoo  before i left the house i made sure to dress in something loose that would not be too distracting. as i walk the streets of new york at night,one hand holds my groceries tightly, the other holds my pocket knife. i walk with urgency, my hoodie is up and my headphones in and,which are not playing music, act like a barrier between the men who catcalls and whistles at me. i see a masculine shadow at the end of the street, but i cannot see its owner. i fear itâ€™s a man awaiting my passing. i make a detour and walk across the street. 
as i usually do on a weekend night, i was clubbing and hanging out with my girls. i normally go to gay clubs, but this weekend i went to a straight club.  once i felt a strong grip on my ass, i turned around to say what the hell, but this 6 foot tall frat guy in a polo would not look at me. this is the first time i  had my ass grabbed unsolicitedly. they have the balls to grab me, but they donâ€™t own up to their actions. every 5 minutes i would take a headcount of my girls because the cocky boys would not listen to us when we said we did not want to grind with them. this was the first night where i saw that the boys were not listening to no. it made me wonder why they felt because it was dark and the music was loud that they could do what they want. i was not being listened to. â€œthere is no greater threat to women than men? weâ€™re the number one threat!â€ said louis c.k. in his hbo special. when are men taught to acknowledge boundaries? i should be able to leave and feel safe wherever i go without having to worry. i am tired with the way that men are treating me and other women. every women has there own story with harassment, but to tell mine i am using barbie as my proxy. when i was younger i looked up to her and she was a beacon of indepence and i vividly remember watching rapunzel barbie in my bubblegum pink room thinking â€œlook at all that she can do for herselfâ€. #photo #photography #art #camera #canon #fujifilm #fujitx1 #digital #digitalphoto #digitalphotography #digitalphotos #mirrorless #metoo #barbie #pink #hair #violent #ken #sexualassult

text:
when you have grown up in abuse, married into abuse or have been around an abusive paradigm for long enough it becomes your normal. itâ€™s all you know so your perspective on what abuse actually is gets distorted. this distortion can get passed down generationally and looks like , oh, thatâ€™s just how your mom is,â€ or, â€œyou need to just show love to your uncle, heâ€™s just got a short temper and heâ€™s been under a lot of stress.â€ no. ğŸ”¥ğŸ”¥ğŸ”¥. let me tell you what abuse is: 
cheating on you, lying, screaming at you, withholding love, silent treatments, adultery, gaslighting (trying to make you believe the abuse isnâ€™t actually happening), deflecting blame back onto you, minimizing your feelings, sarcastic, rude comments, justification of the abuse, â€œwell, you provoked me,â€ smearing you to others behind your back, triangulating you with others, lying about you to others, evading accountability, failure to make amends, shaming you, creating chaos, disrespecting your boundaries, telling you youâ€™re conditionally loving them when you put up boundaries, projecting their bad behaviors onto you, asking you to â€œbuy intoâ€ anyoneâ€™s behavior or to show â€œunconditional loveâ€ to anyone that is abusing you or anyone else. 
these are all forms of abuse. 
i pledge that with the #metoo movement you will see more and more victims in 2019 speak out to claim their redemption after being abused. many times as victims you have this strange twist in your brain that you are somehow the perpetrator, and if you speak out then youâ€™re either bitter or mentally unhinged.

again, another tactic to keep you quiet and to keep the abuse going. 
in order to heal from abuse you must learn what it is, call it out and then speak your truth. otherwise you run the risk of the generation behind you repeating the same dysfunctional system.  tag someone that needs to see this- that needs to understand what theyâ€™ve been dealing with. when does it stop? when you say it does.

in conjunction with our production of #grace, nightwood is proud to present a free symposium on saturday, january 12, 4pm-6pm, onstage at @crowstheatre. .

the symposium will consist of two panels: . .
the failure of justice
with guest speakers the hon. justice rebecca shamai; defence lawyer megan savard of addario law group llp; and deepa mattoo, director of legal services at the barbra schlifer commemorative clinic.
moderated by christine mcgoey . .
.
.the psychology of memory
with guest speakers dr. amy gajaria, child and adolescent psychiatrist; dr. lori haskell, academic research associate with the centre for research & education on violence against women and children; and psychotherapist brenda ponic, founder of the gta adult survivors of child sexual abuse service provider network.
.
.

free to attend - please rsvp for your free ticket at gracesymposium.brownpapertickets.com .
.

nightwood theatreâ€™s community engagement program is generously sponsored by @td_canada .
.

.

text:
women, i have something that i want to share with you. you know me from my training called, "public speaking bootcamp for women" (link in bio). you might also know that i'm writing a book about strengthening women's voices (due april 17th). what you might not know is that i've been a feminist activist all my life. i was so vocal about feminist issues as a teenager that in my 1991 high school yearbook, when others were voted "best hair" or "best style", i was voted "most likely to start a new feminist movement". this label was not a compliment. it was meant as a put-down, but i didn't give a shit. i wore it proudly, as i do today. although i haven't started a new movement, i've kept growing and learning about intersectional feminism, and have participated in the #metoo and #timesup campaigns. i donate my time and money to feminist orgs, like naral, the aclu, and planned parenthood. 
so why do i bring this up?
as a professional voice coach specializing in working women, i am often hired to come into a workplace and give my bootcamp. women often tell me that once this connection and shared strength is in place, they can even work together to push back on forces of workplace sexism. right on!
recently i have been contacted by some orgs that are, in my view, not good for women. theyâ€™ve offered to pay my corporate rates for the bootcamp. any self-employed person will tell you that this is the "dream client" scenario. but i just can't work for any employer that doesn't support women's political, social, and economic equality.
so here's what i want to say: if you hire me as your private or group coach, i will work my ass off to make sure you gain a strong, supported voice. i'll also encourage you do to anything you want with it *except actively oppress other women*. if that's you're jam, then i'm not your coach. nope.
i realize that this means i might lose some business. in any case, whatever you chose to do with your voice and your life, i hope you will recognize that until every woman's voice is heard, we have no voice at all. no one is free until we're all free. 
shout at me in the comments! #voicecoach #publicspeakingcoach #feminism #metoo #timesup

text: i grew up with a camelia rose bush a large as a tree; and, i often recall how i would perch myself beside it, on the steps, almost hidden by its size, and just soak in the outside beauty...and the graceful birds...and the fragrance of everything, from freshly cut grass to the other american beauty roses on the edge of my childhood home...it was where i felt the greatest peace and belonging within what was and is still beautiful in this world. i have never been able to recapture this since...sadly, due to not yet attracting supportive persons as potential life partners. though my heart has always sought peace, i am surprised when i think of how many showed up on my journey not to bring peace, but war to my door. some people just cannot live and let others blossom for who god made them to be...and with those experiences i still havenâ€™t lost my desire to see good people flourish and walk in the beauty or nobility god made them to inhabit...and donâ€™t want to either! ğŸ˜Œ #metoo #metoomovement #timesup #autism #fashionfotoge #fashionfotog #fashionfotogevita #evita #photographer #travelwriter #camilaroses #roses #fllowers #wildlifephotographer #fashionphotographer #runwaycoach #actingcoach #videographer #artdirector #copywriter #graphicdesign #musicphotographer #petportraits #interiordesign #lifestyle #style #copywriter #songwriter #weddings #flowers #camelia

text:
do you want to start a business? is it something youâ€™re truly passionate about? if you answered yes, then please read this! i created a beverage in my kitchen and when people loved it as much as i did i thought, i can do this! i donâ€™t have any beverage experience, iâ€™ve never worked for a beverage company, iâ€™m not a flavor chemist, iâ€™ve never even seen a beverage manufacturing plant. i also donâ€™t have contacts to retail stores or restaurants and i donâ€™t even know how or where to go to create a formula to get my product bottles. could i have easily said, i donâ€™t know any of this so how can i possibly create a beverage brand that could be sold in stores like target and major grocery chains.  hell yes!  but did i let any of those obstacles stop me? hell no! why?  because this was my passion. i wanted to build an all natural organic amazing tasting beverage that once it became a success, i could then take the story of my journey and help inspire others to follow their passion. 
did i grow a beverage brand nationally?  hell yes!  was it easy? hell no!  did i stay up until 4am most nights? absolutely!  did i reach out to every single person i could find on the internet for guidance? absolutely! 
who or what is stopping you from doing what you truly want to do? are you creating excuses of why you canâ€™t?
just remember we all have self-doubt. were there times along my journey where i thought to myself, why am i doing this? whoâ€™s going to buy my beverage? were there nights that i would cry myself to sleep because i didnâ€™t know how i was going to get money to pay for the next production run? absolutely! everybody has self-doubts and if everyone listened there wouldnâ€™t be all the amazing entrepreneurs that exist today.  donâ€™t look at the people who havenâ€™t made it, look at the people who have. look at the successful entrepreneurs and follow what they did. research it. memorize it. live it. if you want this bad enough you will give it your all and that will be the difference between the entrepreneur thatâ€™s successful and the one that doesnâ€™t get to see what they could accomplish.  if i can do it, if anyone can, you can too! xo #youglowgirl

text:
b r e a t h e
â€¢
with the new year comes new sets of resolutions, lofty goals to live up to, and exhausting pressure from the outside world to make 2019 better than the last. dieting, detoxes, exercise, self-improvement plansâ€”these conversations sometimes kick up the dust on those triggering wounds from the past. weâ€™re here to remind you...itâ€™s ok to relax, breathe, and move at your own pace.
â€¢
similar to the breathwork that weâ€™ll be diving into on our retreat, we wanted to provide you with breathing exercises to keep you grounded and calm during this potentially stressful time of the year. deep, diaphragmatic breaths can slow the heartbeat and stabilize or lower blood pressure, helping to calm the body and mind. try these out as needed...
â€¢
1st: humming bee breath: lie in a comfortable position. close your eyes, and plug your ears using your index fingers. with your mouth closed, inhale for six counts through the nostrils. after a full inhalation (expanding into the belly), begin making a gentle, soothing and humming sound in your throat as you exhale six counts through the nostrils. do a few regular humming breaths, keeping the inhales and exhales equal as you do so. then, gradually lengthen the exhalation, if possible, to make it twice as long as the inhalation.
â€¢
2nd: ujjayi -or- ocean breath: both inhalation and exhalation are through the nose. start by lying comfortably on your back. inhale and exhale deeply through your nostrils, slightly constricting your throat so that you can bringing attention to the sound of the breath in your throat. feel and hear the air as it passes through; it usually makes a kind of whooshing sound, similar to when you fog up a mirror with your breath, or the general sound of the ocean. this allows you to clear the mind, bringing all attention to your breathing. continue until you are calm, about a minute or two.

text:
i am proud to join @nataliecrawfordmd and so many other women and female physicians in celebrating the year of the woman by sharing our common struggles #asawoman.
-
as a woman in medicine, i have experienced sexism from patients and their families, colleagues and my supervisors. many of us know what it feels like to be asked your age weekly, to be told youâ€™re â€œtoo prettyâ€ to be the doctor. some of us have had patients feel that they can touch our pregnant bellies and comment on our bodies, even expose themselves to us while we attempt to examine them at the bedside.
-
what i have experienced in clinical medicine, though, does not compare to what i felt as being a member of a healthcare start-up along with two highly successful, older men. as you might imagine, when meeting with hospital administrators, i was frequently ignored. sometimes i was even dressed down. when i wrote emails, responses were directed to my business partners and i was left out. -
and i was the chief medical officer. -
my experiences there made me realize how far we as women still have to go, for our own futures and for our daughters and sons.
-
and yet, i recognize we have already come so far. as i watched the movie sixteen candles for the first time this week, i was appalled to see behavior that we would now consider assault was normalized back in the 80s. and this gives me hope for our shared future. -
the #metoo movement and social media platforms such as this hashtag continue to bring women and female empowerment to the forefront. for that, i am thankful to be able to lend my voice in support of the year of the woman.
#asawoman 
#yearofthewoman #womensupportingwomen #womeninmedicine #womeninwhitecoats #femaleempowerment

.

walking through life being judged,

text:
as many of you know, i had the opportunity to travel to nepal last summer for my internship. i was able to come along side @lovejusticeintl to create compelling stories that help people understand and relate to human trafficking.

this month is human trafficking awareness month. a lot of people acknowledge that human trafficking happens, but not everyone is aware how or on what scale it happens.

today, there are over 40 million people enslaved, forced into manual labor and/or sex.

@lovejusticeintl attacks human trafficking at the most strategic point: while a person is being trafficked. lji sends them to safety, while at the same time gathering data and arresting and convicting traffickers.

this month i will be telling my story of how i came to be so passionate about human trafficking awareness. i hope youâ€™ll follow along.

every life is beautiful and worth fighting for.

text:
ğŸš¨long post alert!ğŸš¨ i waited a few days to start writing this out and post it because honestly, itâ€™s probably the most important & personal thing iâ€™m ever going to say on a public platform. i really didnâ€™t want it to get lost in a sea of â€œnew year, new meâ€ posts. 
one year ago, i left not only a dysfunctional, toxic relationship, but in that process i lost and was forced to grieve my little family. at first, i was distracted by the elation of newfound freedom; i ignored my grief. but like most things, the more we shove down, the bigger the explosion when it finally all spills out.

i have struggled with chronic depression and suicidal thoughts since i was 11 and six months ago, i was swallowed by it yet again. this time, it was the most crippling depression iâ€™ve ever experienced. i almost lost my job, i literally couldnâ€™t get myself out of bed somedays. everyone had their own advice...â€exerciseâ€ â€œdrink more waterâ€ â€œwhenâ€™s the last time you saw your therapist?â€ â€œthrow yourself into your work to distract you!â€ nothing worked. because iâ€™m responsible for another human being, i set aside my pride, my previous beliefs; i went and saw a psychiatrist. he diagnosed me with chronic major depression and explained what iâ€™d been going through. he said since i struggled with depression since age 11, itâ€™s likely that my brain has never produced enough serotonin and therefore left me with a major chemical imbalance. he prescribed me zoloft, and in just 2 weeks, i began to feel the change. itâ€™s been a little over 4 months now, and iâ€™m the best i have ever been. i feel hope, i feel joy, i feel disappointment. but for the first time, iâ€™m finally healthy. iâ€™m finally able to cope. i am truly happy. *caption was too long; more in comments*

text:
jaishri abichandani, grief and glory, 2017-18, mixed media, 32 x 32 x 39in. (81 x 81 x 99cm)
_______________
"this work is dedicated to black trans women who are being killed at extraordinary rates. the triceratops stands as much for that fossilized ideology that causes the death of these women as to carnival." - jaishri abichandani
_______________
jaishri abichandani has made recent news for her significant participation in the #metoo movement, but her artwork has always been steeped in intersectional feminism. as much an examination of injustices against trans women of color as it is a devoted celebration of their existence, the work's title, "grief and glory" summarizes the intent beautifully.  shimmering and adorned with beetle wings and swarovski crystals, the sculpture is a heartfelt tribute to power and beauty in the face of adversity. 
_______________
"grief and glory" will be on display at c24 gallery for "transfigured". join us for an opening reception on january 10th from 6-8pm. the exhibition runs from january 10th - february 23, 2019.
.

text:
i blinked and five years went by since the release of dear sister: letters from survivors of sexual violence. it took thirteen years from book concept to publication, and now, on its fifth anniversary, i still continue to receive messages from people who read the book and share how it has impacted their lives. it  moves me beyond words: repaired family relationships, healing circles among incarcerated survivors, boyfriends trying to understand, girlfriends trying to survive, desperate parents, angry friendsâ€”every story matters.

it was 2014 when dear sister was publishedâ€”before the #metoo movement, before anthologies by and for survivors was considered marketable or even legitimate, before mainstream media began covering sexual violence as a feature story of cultural significance and not just individually profiling cases for broadcasting journalism. i mention those markers not to illustrate how groundbreaking the anthology was, but to underscore the leap the contributors took in order to share their stories with me and turn it into a road map for others. no one had published anything like this before which is also why i remain grateful to ak press for the leap they took with me, for the chances they extend to books that must singe their own path.

now through january 6, all ak press books are 50% off. which means you can accomplish two things: 1. support ak press and 2. buy the dear sister anthology and gift it to local libraries, coalitions, organizations, crisis centers, universities and colleges, or to a friend or family member.

to dear sister's five year anniversary, and to all who observe anniversaries of survival, this book has always been dedicated to you.

#believesurvivors #dearsisterfiveyearanniversary

text: it seems like everyone had a #horrible2018 except for me. in 2017 i was in a horrible job and being mentally tortured and #sexuallyharassed. right after i filed a workers comp claim the #metoo #movement happened which completely helped my case because wasn't such a long shot anymore. my #hero #doctor actually put me out on disability because i was so physically ill by the end of 2017. i had been #hospitalized several times i had lost a ton of weight, i couldn't hold any food down, i was getting #migraines and constantly #sleepwalking giving myself #concussions from all of the stress of my prior job. #tza was actually the one who gave me the courage to get out of the situation and was so upset that this boss was doing this to me. she got me my #great #attorneys as of january 1, 2018 they put me on disability and i easily  won my worker's comp. case. i needed this year off to heal with a lot of counseling quite a few mental breakdowns many trips to the doctors i was able to handle this all somehow on my own. i had a very difficult cancer of the labia surgery in april which was something i wouldn't wish on my worst enemy currently i found a lump on my breast and i don't care. i often wonder where i get the strength to do this life thing. i guess i was just #bornthisway  i was so #depressed i wasn't getting out of bed my downstairs neighbor was doing the dog walking thing through #rover and i thought this might be good therapy to take a dog out once in a while and give myself some exercise and get out of the house. my doctors all liked the #idea as well. it turned out to be the best therapy ever and a new job and a new chapter in my life because now i'm in high demand with over  25 five star reviews and no negative reviews! people constantly referring me word-of-mouth these #dogs and #cats have been #livesavers literally life has always been throwing wrenches into my mix but as long as nobody died last year well i think i had a pretty good year! here's to an even better 2019 #healingisaprocess #slowlybutsurely #lifegoeson #lifeafterdeath
name: Colleen
tweet_full: it seems like everyone had a #horrible2018 except for me. in 2017 i was in a horrible job and being mentally tortured and #sexuallyharassed. right after i filed a workers comp claim the #metoo #movement happened which completely helped my case because wasn't such a long shot anymore. my #hero #doctor actually put me out on disability because i was so physically ill by the end of 2017. i had been #hospitalized several times i had lost a ton of weight, i couldn't hold any food down, i was getting #migraines and constantly #sleepwalking giving myself #concussions from all of the stress of my prior job. #tza was actually the one who gave me the courage to get out of the situation and was so upset that this boss was doing this to me. she got me my #great #attorneys as of january 1, 2018 they put me on disability and i easily  won my worker's comp. case. i needed this year off to heal with a lot of counseling quite a few mental breakdowns many trips to the doctors i was able to handle this all somehow on my own. i had a very difficult cancer of the labia surgery in april which was something i would not wish on my worst enemy currently i found a lump on my breast and i do not care. i often wonder where i get the strength to do this life thing. i guess i was just #bornthisway  i was so #depressed i wasn't getting out of bed my downstairs neighbor was doing the dog walking thing through #rover and i thought this might be good therapy to take a dog out once in a while and give myself some exercise and get out of the house. my doctors all liked the #idea as well. it turned out to be the best therapy ever and a new job and a new chapter in my life because now i am in high demand with over  25 five star reviews and no negative reviews! people constantly referring me word-of-mouth these #dogs and #cats have been #livesavers literally life has always been throwing wrenches into my mix but as long as nobody died last year well i think i had a pretty good year! here's to an even better 2019 #healingisaprocess #slowlybutsurely #lifegoeson #lifeafterdeath

text:
california walnut creek cheesecake factory  workers assaults a black man with high functioning autism calling him retarded and a n####r. 
he made a complaint because the workers called him retarded as he tried to communicate his confirmation number then they banned him from the store after its workers were caught on camera menacing him and threatening to assault him in a threatening stance and balling their fist should he return all because he had a speech communication disorder.

one worker was overheard telling the man your people should just stay in oakland. a customer also joined im the verbal attack calling him a retarded n#####. another worker refused to be the mans witness and stated "i'm not in this" on camera.

officers responded after the man with autism called police due to being threatened by the workers and manager. the officers response was to refuse to file a report and to conduct a search of the man without probable cause then threatened him that if he returns despite no trespass order in effect he will be arrested. 
we reached out to corporate for comment however were told nothing had been done about it. they then told us their not concerned and hungup in our face. 
this is in no way an isolated inciden.

in 2017 three black women are suing the cheesecake factory, alleging they were discriminated against during a 2017 visit to the redondo beach restaurant by a male white server who used the term "you people" and by a manager who told them, "you are nobody." this seems common for discrimination to occur  at this merchant and management has done nothing to stop it.

this matter is currently under investigation by the bay chronicles. 
video will be released soon after the investigation.

text:
look at all of the different religious doctrines being used to swear in our 116th congress/wo/men. a historic day in america... where the faces of power are changing. where new interests will get their shot at making change. it's easy to be cynical and think that nothing makes a difference in this racist, classist, imperialist system...
.
but america has never been so diverse. we're in the modern civil rights era. why else would people be getting killed in the streets in record numbers by police? why else would our incarceration rate be the highest in the world in the country that encourages democratic participation? why else would we see record numbers of deportations and marginalization of nonwhite immigrants? using the force of the state to take leaders out of communities and discourage poor people, black people, and brown people from having a public life.... we've never had so many beautiful women and brown people with money to throw at causes they believe in. and as long as we preserve/defend the republic, our numbers will always mean something.
.
real change comes from the community. but getting people in the system before people can change the rules is an equally important task...
.
#116thcongress #changeinthemaking #occupy #blm #metoo #namesomeotherorgsthataremakingnationalwaves

text:
in 2017 i was held captive for 2 days, beaten, strangled until blood vessels in my eyes burst and sexually assaulted at the hands of someone i thought loved me.
i have never spoken publicly about this incident because i was ashamed and to some degree still am. 
the trial starts next week and i am hoping to finally put this incident behind me. it has effected every area of my life, my family, my ability to sleep and my tendency to self medicate. i have held onto fear and self loathing because i felt at fault. i hid from my friends and family and sank into addiction. i hope every other woman going through this knows they are not alone. i have to remind myself daily that i am not to blame, that i am loveable and that i shouldn't be ashamed of what happened. if anyone else out there is experiencing this, you're not alone and the more we speak the better it gets. i'm moving forward stronger and wiser. #domesticviolence #survivor #speakup #speakout #notalone #metoo #stopdomesticviolence

fend off chapped, flaky lips or even add a pop of color to your pout with a homemade tinted gloss made from coconut oil. to make it, simply mix bits of an old lipstick with some coconut oil.

text: i won this shirt from skincare company @paulaschoice and the message couldnâ€™t be more fitting! for the last several years my fight has been to advocate for survivors of abuse and trauma and to empower them to know they are worthy of love and healing by cultivating communities of support, self-care and compassion. along with @allthehealthy i am working on education and empowerment so that young people know how to identify abuse, intervene, and speak out against it. we have turned our social media presence @warriorsbybtfp into a non-profit that will focus on connecting survivors to resources and lobbying for legislative change around the #metoo movement. itâ€™s scary, intimidating and requires a lot of confidence and courage to envision the change we want to see in the world. but we are organized and determined. this shirt represents the risk we are taking, because we will be fundraising to support ourselves and make our dreams come true! #choosethefight #empowerment #skincare #newyear #newme #warriors #metoo #timesup

text:
for masculinity, look within

i made a mistake in a post last year, due to an error in knowledge and a gap in awareness.

i stated that the #metoo movement was an opportunity for the collective anger of women to help men discover their masculinity â€” and urged women to tell men â€œwhat they need to know.â€ the truth, and it may sound blasphemous because the prevailing social wisdom says otherwise, is this:

men should look to men. period. men cannot learn a manâ€™s masculinity from a woman any more than a woman can learn a woman's femininity from a man. and within that, it's all self-discovery.

thatâ€™s it.

and the truth of that is easily demonstrated by flipping my original statement: â€œthe #metoo movement is an opporutnity for the collective anger of men to help women discover their femininity .. i urge men to tell women what they need to know.â€ sounds wrong, doesnâ€™t it?

right now, we have a generation of men raised mostly by women, men who are more feminine than any generation in history, with sperm counts at their lowest in recorded history. as this pattern continues, and as divorce and single-motherhood rates continue to rise, whatâ€™s the end result?

if youâ€™ve ever wondered â€œwhere are all the good men?,â€ look no further.

this is not meant as a conspiracy to blame women. it is, however, meant as a spiritual and sociological challenge to the idea that men should look to women to determine what is positive masculinity.

why? because we already have a generation of men raised within the feminine-centric paradigm â€” and â€œtoxic masculinityâ€ and #metoo arose within it.

stay tuned.
.
.
.

text:
coconut for skin and body

hydrate dry hands

coconut oil can work wonders on dry, itchy skin.Â keep a jar of organic extra virgin coconut oil by the kitchen sink and put a little on after washing your hands to keep them soft and moist.

use in place of lotion

coconut oil is a commonly used as a hydrating oil in its raw form or as an ingredient in moisturizers. simply use it as your go-to moisturizer if youâ€™re looking for an affordable option that not only smells amazing, but also leaves your skin feeling nourished and smooth.

slather on as a massage oil

many store-bought massage oils have either coconut or jojoba oil as their base. cut out the middleman and go straight to the bottle. itâ€™s slippery, skin-friendly, and moisturizing.

create a luscious body scrub

make a body scrub yourself with ingredients you already have in your kitchen. itâ€™s wonderfully moisturizing, great for the skin, inexpensive, and blissfully absent of chemicals you canâ€™t pronounce.

nourish dry cuticles

massaging coconut oil into your cuticles and the skin around your nails can bring some much-needed moisture to an often overlooked part of the body. the benefit? youâ€™ll fend off cracked skin, hydrate brittle nails, and prevent hang nails.

relieve psoriasis

coconut oil is a safe natural remedy to try if you suffer from psoriasis, an autoimmune disease that causes skin cells to build up, which leads to rough, red, scaly patches. aside from making a hot bath even more luxurious, adding a couple of tablespoons of coconut oil to the tub can relieve itchy, scaly skin caused by psoriasis and moisturize your skin.

soothe eczema

coconut oil can also be used as a natural treatment option for those with eczema, a cluster of skin issues that lead to red, itchy, swollen patches of skin. apply a light layer of virgin coconut oil to the affected area twice a day to help soothe eczema.

apply as natural lubricant during sex

pure 100 percent coconut oil makes a great natural lubricant, since itâ€™s super slippery. itâ€™s very rare for people to have any type of allergic reaction to it.

an icon of power, speaker pelosi takes the gavel for the second time in her career. she is the only woman to be elected speaker the us house of representatives. the #116thcongress is the most diverse in history. in the us house, 102 women will serve. two native american (first nation) women join the us congress, sharice davids and deb haaland. the youngest ever elected woman, alexandria ocasio-cortez, will be sworn in at age 29. ayanna pressley will serve as the first african american woman representing massachusetts. rashida tlaib will serve as the first muslim representing michigan's 13th district. the first muslim to represent minnesota's 5th district is ilhan omar, who came to america 23 years ago as a refugee. this congress boasts the largest congressional black caucus in history.

the awarding of the nobel peace prize to nadia murad, a survivor, and dr. denis mukwege for fighting sexual violence as a weapon of war sent a signal that globally, a reckoning is underway. 
the peaceful transition of power relies on our collective dedication to each other's humanity. women's role in leadership, in power, in driving the economy and culture, is certain and timeless. speaker pelosi, #wesaluteyou. ğŸ“·: @platon

text:
on october 22nd, 2018, lauren mccluskey, a 21-year-old university ofÂ utahÂ student, was on the phone with her parents when she was attacked. her parents called campus police and 911, overhearing her screams, but it was too late. lauren's ex boyfriend, 37-year old melvin rowland, shot her in the head and killed her. police pursued him, and he ultimately committed suicide during the chase.

but lauren's death was preventable. lauren called the police 6 times in the 10 days before her murder with an increasing level of distress and fear for her life. the campus police at university of utah and the local pd failed to protect lauren, telling her repeatedly that the text messages did not rise to the level of harassment and that the investigation would take time.

lauren wasÂ found dead in the back seat of a parked carÂ that same night after rowland, whom sheâ€™d dated for about a month and lied to her about his name, age and criminal background. rowland wasÂ convicted of attempted forcible sex abuseÂ and enticing a minor over the internet in 2004. lauren is a part of a growing epidemic of women who are murdered by an intimate partner following ending the relationship.

the university report cites â€œshortcomingsâ€ in the system, such as â€œgaps in training, awareness, and enforcement of certain policies rather than lapses in individual performanceâ€ when describing how campus police handled mccluskeyâ€™s case.
still, university officials said in the report they donâ€™t believe they could have stopped rowland from murdering mccluskey. campus police failing to check his parole status after finding out about his criminal background is not a "shortcoming," that is one of the many failures that cost lauren her life. 
leave a ğŸ’œ in the comments for lauren and all those lost to domestic violence.

text:
you have to ask and you have to say yes. we always talk about consent this and consent that but the truth is there are so many grey areas when it comes to the nuances of sexual behaviors and communication. the fact of the matter is, everyone is raised differently with various skills in communication and this makes sex particularly tricky. one party is not solely responsible in being the gatekeeper for sex but our culture and media has made us believe it to be so. sex is supposed to pleasurable and it's supposed to be a process so it should involve some type of communication throughout involving reassurances on whether you both enjoy this or is this position okay or not etc. instead, we are all brainwashed to believe silence and mindreading are what's "sexy" and we grunt in silence and sometimes pain. is that "sexy" to you? #foodforthought
if you want to learn how to ask for consent organically or how to practice assertive communication, we are here for you! we have trained, approachable and relevant professionals mon-thurs to help young people <3

i drew this new yearâ€™s comic in my sketchbook just for myself, but iâ€™m gonna share it because change starts with stating out loud that youâ€™re aiming for it. 2018 was a revelatory personal year on a lot of levels, but mostly in terms of what i am willing to tolerate from men. the combination of 1. #metoo 2. a professional shift into becoming a feminist historian and 3. some personal bullshit all served as the cumulative last straw in my bending to accommodate entitled men. 
moving forward, iâ€™m holding my romantic relationships to the same standards of generosity, equity, and respect that i have in my platonic relationships. i suspect that this means iâ€™ve got a very long spell of being single in my future, but in the words of poet ijeoma umbinyuo: â€œi am too full of life/to be half loved.â€
the hardest part of breaking a pattern is reaching the internal place of being done with it, and it feels reallyâ€”reallyâ€” good to be going into 2019 feeling done down to the marrow of my bones.

text:
[1/5] as 2018 has ended i have had a moment to reflect, i look back and see this past year as one of major ups and downs. running your own business is hard work - it requires commitment, grit, and resilience. not only am i carrying the weight of continuing to make it on my own, but i also have scars from a traumatic childhood that i have to breathe around every single day. in early 2017, i saw the #metoo movement gain momentum around me as many women came out and spoke about their experiences with sexual assault. it was then when one of my deepest truths, the fact that i had been molested as a child by a relative, started to be relived within the walls of my mind. i remember thinking to myself, â€œyou can actually speak about this?â€ i come from a community of south asian immigrants that abides by a â€œsweep under the f*ckin rugâ€ culture that made my speaking out more prolonged than it needed to be. i spent my childhood swallowed by my own silence and my inability to feel safe in telling anyone about my experience. the inspiration that the #metoo movement ignited in me let me know that my time to finally speak my truth was near and i collaborated with @browngirlmag and @sakhinyc to put together a panel of south asian women to share their stories of surviving sexual assault. the event took place in march of 2018 and was a success, i felt freer than i have ever felt before. being in a room full of other women who were fellow survivors gave me the sense of connection i was missing as a child. one of my goals in 2019 is to keep the trend of openness going with my friends and followers. the more i can share with you all about my experiences, the more i can impact lives and spark change around an issue that we have just skimmed the surface in talking about. recently, i stumbled upon a set of posts from @wendyslookbook that have pushed me to tell my story in more detail and to describe my journey as a survivor. drawing inspiration from wendy, i have come together with my team to create a narrative that best describes what i went through. this is my story, #metoo. ğŸ“¸ @tarasharma

text:
modeled after the nyc city council's 1989 choking victim poster, this was designed by karen leibowitz co-owner of the perennial in san francisco. it was created in response to the #metoo movement that she saw encouraged many bay area women to talk about their sexual assault stories as well.
~
"the ultimate goal is to make institutional anti-harassment messages so ubiquitous that if someone showed up for her first day of work at a restaurant and didnâ€™t see a poster on display, sheâ€™d consider it a red flag" 
#metoo and other movements that drive conversation around sexual assault and sexual violence encourage others to speak out, but how do we really push towards a shift in culture? for one, we need to acknowledge the different experiences women have with sexual assault in the work place. we are glad this is being brought to light, but historically service industry workers, especially women have not been prioritized when it comes to their rights. this must change! .
.
.
#twbwomensmarch #twbforsurvivors #womenswave #truthtopower

text:
a breakthrough is not an epiphany though the terms seem interchangeable. an epiphany is more like a new idea. a breakthrough happens when a new layer has been accessed on a subject. an example of this i recently had was that beneath a blanket of shame that i have poured so much energy into justifying was a 20 year old rage that i had not allowed myself to feel towards someone close. when we are children we decide that the reason horrible things happen to us is because we are horrible. this makes us feel safer because we do not blame the outside world and only ourselves. we adopt the identity of being horrible into our personality keeping us from having the self-confidence needed to aspire. once someone can break through that notion of deserving abuse they can feel the other associated emotions like the rage of the unfairness that it had happened. withought being able to feel the unfairness of what has happened to you it can be impossible to forgive someone.
- - - - - - - - - - - - - method - - - - - - - - - - - - -
1) stop telling the story that you deserved it.
2) access the pain of betrayal (e.g. being abused, not being protected, a harmful situation)
3) feel the unfairness completely, without justification until the physical response deminishes (e.g. gut wrenching feeling, closed throat, groin pressure, headaches)
4) ensure that your current life does not reflect any of the abusive patterns you are trying to forgive. if so remove yourself from the situation completely.
- now you are in a place to be able to forgive without forcing it.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
lifetimesâ€™s â€œsurviving  r. kellyâ€ docuseries aires today. 9/8 central. iâ€™m certain it took great strength for those survivors  to share  their experiences.  the previews alone have brought  out the ugly in social media.  r. kelly has been muted in my book.  the red flags have already been there. those that choose to continue to support him are nothing more than enablers who cosign the narrative that black women and their pain donâ€™t matter. .
.
.

according the â€œsexual violence victimization and associations with health in a community sample of african american womenâ€ - a recent study conducted by the national sexual violence resource center, 73% of the women surveyed were under the age of 18 when they experienced  their first unwanted sexual experience and  96% percent of them knew their perpetrator. .
.
.

unlike some, i donâ€™t need a conviction to know  r. kelly is a pedophile and sexual perpetrator.  his marriage to the then underaged alyiah was a huge red flag. furthermore, the type of support he continues to receive despite the facts, highlights why sexual trauma and violence goes underreported in the black community. some would much rather look the other way because they enjoy the benefits of the perpetrator. .
.
.

one of the worst experiences in life is having to confront your perpetrator. to not have community support or be labled as a liar or trouble maker only adds insult to injury. .
.
.

sending  light, strength, peace and complete healing to those survivors.  #muterkelly #metoo ğŸ¥lifetime

the woman who crocheted this bedspread worked as a bomb inspector during wwii. she had to wear stockings, heels and a full girdle to work while using calipers to measure bombs for imperfections. when she rejected too many because of faulty materials or construction, her superiors made her adjust her standards so they could meet production quotas...even if it meant a bomb might explode in the hold of an aircraft. i donâ€™t know if she ever stood up to these men, or if this was even a choice for her. itâ€™s a hell of a story about talented women, their incredible capability and ultimate powerlessness.

text:
"have you ever felt so physically helpless and intensely intimidated by someone's presence that you cease to exist? i hope the answer to that is a straight out no for all of you. i was sexually abused at the age of 7, that's when i was exposed to that particular feeling. the person worked as a house help in my home.

for the rest of my childhood and early teenage years, i had no recollection of those memories at all. 
compartmentalization is a real thing folks.

fast forward to first year of college, where i decided to do something about never feeling that way again. so i joined a mixed martial arts school in delhi. that's where and how i got introduced to jiu jitsu. it was a straight out love affair from there on. i was fascinated by how it acted as an equaliser and leveled the playing field up to a certain point. it didn't matter if i was small, skiny or weak. with jiu jitsu and a little work on myself i could be a person who could have his back.

the biggest thing that rolling and jiu jitsu does for me is that it keeps me honest with myself. it has given me immense confidence of certain kind. from being a liability, i grew into being a pillar for others. it shows me my weaknesses, shows me what i lack and where more effort is required. after every roll you get to learn about something, be it about jiu jitsu, yourself or just about life through jiu jitsu.

and i learn all of this highly philosophical shit while having insane amounts of fun. for people who don't practice jiu jitsu and can't relate, it's like you're having your favourite pizza and getting to know all these great truths from the pizza. i know! it's one of the best things in the world. talking about rolling here, having pizza comes in second"

#oss

text:
we welcome you to this yearâ€™s pathways to vday auditions! pathways to vday is a multicultural and multilingual performance of eve ensler's "the vagina monologues". we are looking for brave female-identified/gender neutral individuals to join our pathways performance. so long as you are comfortable speaking about female/vagina issues, are comfortable saying vagina really loud and in multiple languages, to a crowd, then we hope you will audition.

we are pleased to share that the vday.org leadership has given pathways for change, inc. special permission to perform this year in april for sexual assault awareness month! the 2018 performance was plagued by snow and ice, performing later in the year will hopefully get us through our messy snow season to ensure performers and audience safety. we are tremendously grateful to the vday.org team for their spirit and thoughtfulness. â€œthe vagina monologues is made up of various personal monologues read by a diverse group of women. originally, eve ensler performed every monologue herself, with subsequent performances featuring three actresses, and more recent versions featuring a different actress for every role. each of the monologues deals with an aspect of the feminine experience, touching on matters such as sex, sex work, body image, love, rape, menstruation, female genital mutilation, masturbation, birth, orgasm, the various common names for the vagina or simply as a physical aspect of the body. a recurring theme throughout the piece is the vagina as a tool of female empowerment, and the ultimate embodiment of individuality." (thank you wikipedia)

to let us know if you are interested , visit: http://pathwaystovdayauditions.eventbrite.com/?s=90591445 
for questions/info: 
hleboeuf@pathwaysforchange.help or 508-852-7600

name: Pathways for Change, Inc.
tweet_full:
we welcome you to this yearâ€™s pathways to vday auditions! pathways to vday is a multicultural and multilingual performance of eve ensler's "the vagina monologues". we are looking for brave female-identified/gender neutral individuals to join our pathways performance. so long as you are comfortable speaking about female/vagina issues, are comfortable saying vagina really loud and in multiple languages, to a crowd, then we hope you will audition.

we are pleased to share that the vday.org leadership has given pathways for change, inc. special permission to perform this year in april for sexual assault awareness month! the 2018 performance was plagued by snow and ice, performing later in the year will hopefully get us through our messy snow season to ensure performers and audience safety. we are tremendously grateful to the vday.org team for their spirit and thoughtfulness. â€œthe vagina monologues is made up of various personal monologues read by a diverse group of women. originally, eve ensler performed every monologue herself, with subsequent performances featuring three actresses, and more recent versions featuring a different actress for every role. each of the monologues deals with an aspect of the feminine experience, touching on matters such as sex, sex work, body image, love, rape, menstruation, female genital mutilation, masturbation, birth, orgasm, the various common names for the vagina or simply as a physical aspect of the body. a recurring theme throughout the piece is the vagina as a tool of female empowerment, and the ultimate embodiment of individuality." (thank you wikipedia)

to let us know if you are interested , visit: http://pathwaystovdayauditions.eventbrite.com/?s=90591445 
for questions/info: 
hleboeuf@pathwaysforchange.help or 508-852-7600
.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnnâ€™s don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from koganâ€™s app may not have been completely deleted. koganâ€™s app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
2018 has been a roller coaster ride for the oppressed and the oppressor, for the helpless and the powerful and for the campaigners and the bashers. from marital rape to homosexuality to #metoo we have come a long way. let us have a look at some of the most important events that india witnessed this year. 
#2 women no more properties of their husbands

in the face of all those men rights activists who believed that the adultery laws in india were biased against men and gave women the â€œpower to cheatâ€ on their husbands with no repercussions, the supreme court rightly observed that the adultery laws in fact violated â€œequality before the lawâ€ and treated women as properties of their husbands. also, itâ€™s funny how some people still think that the court is biased towards women and thatâ€™s why the sc has decriminalized adultery instead of punishing women for the same offence. however, not even one of them has come forward and argued that the criminalization of adultery should be in place because women should also be given an equal right to file an adultery suit against her cheating husband. hypocrisy much?

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters
